  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\n\u003cmain id=\"main\" role=\"main\" tabindex=\"-1\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv data-version=\"2\" id=\"page_body\" name=\"Page Body\"\u003e\n\u003carticle\u003e\n\u003cdiv\u003e\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eSeptember 10, 2024\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eShare this\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"post-body-2431290918527327636\"\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg36m7u2bcmG_Yjx-2xldaQSxcTEyYhsmDRFUYQLBpx1XcG-1CcNByXQqHy_wqc8bgnmqAfcgIAL8Vl901iVmc4M1cVJqhJziJrf_xE5AAevGenZZNUsnw95qBPoCRRhYF-qGLFiccdA60/s1600-h/146_thumb%25255B1%25255D_thumb%25255B4%25255D%25255B3%25255D.jpg\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"9/11 workshop museum art\" height=\"599\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjevN-Jg7TGYmsNqNyo-lMjcvyVkNOyeKHkb-9vwu-O6OqvQjDEp7L7AhTMGH_xMUSnp3BgrnOe-ksXEZCFFVH6ktVDqR4sam5WXiKS2H0DY_rDhKsHvXbedwH4XM_eiq_pyH8sQT5qA7s/rw/?imgmax=1600\" title=\"\" width=\"450\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr/\u003e\nI share this post every year because it\u0026#39;s important to me that we have a visual reminder of this day, now more than 20 years ago. Can you even believe it? \u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003eIt\u0026#39;s crazy to me that there is a whole generation that wasn\u0026#39;t even alive when 9/11 occurred.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\n\nIf you\u0026#39;ve read my blog for long, you know New York City is near and dear to us. It\u0026#39;s a city we love so very much. I always knew I\u0026#39;d love it, and when my husband took me on my first trip (just a few days before September 11, 2001) I found out I was right. \u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\nThis photo always gives me chills. We\u0026#39;re at the top of the Statue of Liberty and you can barely see the towers behind me:\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjGCe-Ay3G1M8Nlhec59SqPNcEaQlDW7nx1gWbFVD8apIuyn1DCy0b7LY7Hvb8gtCsMOJy3Z1v1h_uLIS9JNimZ0FjAQnTJAYiZkgU3I8N2MdI0eX9xckLxC0r0vjfj6cDoTmFPiAl18T8/s1600/before+9%253A11.jpg\"\u003e\u003cimg data-original-height=\"599\" data-original-width=\"450\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjGCe-Ay3G1M8Nlhec59SqPNcEaQlDW7nx1gWbFVD8apIuyn1DCy0b7LY7Hvb8gtCsMOJy3Z1v1h_uLIS9JNimZ0FjAQnTJAYiZkgU3I8N2MdI0eX9xckLxC0r0vjfj6cDoTmFPiAl18T8/s1600-rw/before+9%253A11.jpg?imgmax=1600\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis was nine days before 9/11. Nine days later and the towers were gone.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\n\nMy husband was a band director at the time, and a few months after the attacks we were supposed to travel to Japan for a band trip. \u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003eHe canceled that trip and instead we took the students to New York City. SO many New Yorkers stopped us numerous times and thanked the kids for visiting.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\n\nThese first photos are from the \u003ca href=\"https://groundzeromuseumworkshop.org/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eGround Zero Museum\u003c/a\u003e and tell the story of that day. This location is separate from the new museum — it used to be closer to Ground Zero but it looks like it’s moved to 14th street. If you visit the city I highly recommend visiting both. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\n\nI let the photos do the talking (forgive the quality, all were taken with a phone over the years):\u003cspan\u003e\u003ca name=\"more\"\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr/\u003e\n\u003ca href=\"https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi3jYWIaggDmt6RMW3mQ76uYjNw8sQEbqNM1ZTqzO5FKC-3ZibVgbdel8cfH30EmOZgI-97QtIRv1_YVXP35AaWyVlnL0iZJDElXyzQb4fBwC8eMC2T0WL2c_YtIzm-aIg9SP64Qia9tww/s1600-h/100_thumb%25255B1%25255D_thumb%25255B7%25255D%25255B6%25255D.jpg\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"599\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\